passages.text: We add UCB, Vestas Wind Systems and Konecranes to the Conviction List while removing L'Oreal.

UCB: Bimzelx (c€7bn peak sales, \(12\%\) ahead of consensus) is a rare opportunity within European Biopharma to own a significant blockbuster launch, per Rajan Sharma. He also sees optionality from other mid- stage drugs which could provide an additional leg of growth. Uncertainty around US pricing for the sector more widely provides an attractive entry point post UCB de- rating since the November 2024 peak to 22x from 28x on 12m forward P/E.

Vestas: Ajay Patel highlights that as US energy policy uncertainty clears, Vestas is set for a positive order picture in 2H as well as an improvement in margins as the offshore drag has peaked. This improvement in 2H profitability should drive a sizeable increase in cash generation, strengthening the debate around cash returns.

Konecranes: Daniela Costa sees a structural growth opportunity given Chinese tariffs and incentives for US reshoring, leaving significant upside risk to consensus. She also sees a recovery in Industrial Equipment over the medium term driven by German infrastructure spend (c20% of revenues). Strong cash generation supports increased returns with a total yield of c7%.
In this update we also provide market commentary, review performance and key estimate changes, and highlight upcoming catalysts for the stocks on our Conviction List.

2Q just cleared a low bar but share price reactions were asymmetric. Strategist Guillaume Jaisson notes that Europe only just cleared a bar which had been lowered, with earnings beating \(2\%\) on a headline basis but in- line ex- Financials, despite earnings being revised down \(7\%\) going into the season. YoY growth in 2Q was \(5\%\) but \(- 2\%\) ex- Financials for the STOXX 600 and consensus and GS now expect no earnings growth in 2025 (vs. \(8\%\) expected at the start of the year with downgrades driven by FX). Interestingly, companies that beat expectations saw little share price upside but earnings misses were penalised more than we have seen in c.20 years. Meanwhile in the US, the S&P 500 beat by \(4\%\) and earnings grew \(11\%\) YoY.

Financials were once again a bright spot, with Insurance posting the highest percentage of positive surprises, followed by Diversified Financials and Banks as the top three SXXP sectors. Within Insurance, Andrew Baker has taken a slightly more selective stance into the end of the year; his top pick continues to be SCOR (Buy, on CL). Within Banks, Chris Hallam believes that the 'Better for Longer' backdrop he wrote about here should be able to continue given the rate curve has steepened YTD and credit continues to perform well. He continues to see Buy-rated ING (on CL) as well positioned given its exposure to German fiscal spend, and underappreciated NII upside.

On the flip side, Chemicals had the highest percentage of misses, and Georgina Fraser refreshed her views post a number of high- profile profit warnings. One that bucked the trend was Novonesis (Buy, on CL) as it delivered strong OSG growth against this difficult backdrop but the shares still sold off given short- term margin concerns.

Balancing European growth and French confidence votes. Our European Economist Jari Stehn continues to think Europe can have its moment after having significantly underperformed the US in recent years, especially in terms of productivity growth. Despite some structural headwinds, he expects Europe can improve its economic performance (e.g., increased public investment, leadership in pharma and green tech, financial market reforms), supported more broadly by German fiscal spend which has been widely discussed; he is above consensus on growth especially in Germany out to 2028. France's unexpected confidence vote has reduced investor confidence in Europe at the end of the month, with Alex Stott noting that the most likely outcome is the government losing the confidence vote and being forced to resign which would also make further rating downgrades more likely. The tail risk is elections being called which could lead to concerns around this year's spending but for now our growth forecasts for France are unchanged. Sharon Bell in equity strategy notes that French domestic are most exposed given the outperformance they had YTD before the news (basket GSXEFRDO which includes Unibail- Rodamco- Westfield (Buy, on CL)).

On course for US rate cuts. After weaker job numbers this month, our US macro team's view that US growth is near stall speed has been reinforced, and we continue to expect a 25bp cut in September, consistent with Powell's remarks at Jackson Hole. The dovish Fed expectations (as well as strong US earnings season) has meant that the Goldilocks regime has persisted through the summer.

Capex revival in Europe? Equity Strategist, Guillaume, also looked at data supporting a pick up in capex which supports Daniela Costa's multi- industry Capex Tracker from last month showing a pick up in medium term capex (positive for Atlas Copco (Buy, on CL) as well as new addition to the list Konecranes; see our podcast with Daniela and strategy here). There has been a pick up in the capex to sales ratio in Europe and, more importantly, companies with positive capex revisions are being rewarded by the market (vs. rewarding buybacks over investments, as has been typically the case in the region). Bonus depreciation changes in the US and Germany should further support capex.

Luxury - signs of life in China (off a low base)? We have seen continued positive datapoints in Luxury and this month Louise Singlehurst looked at the most recent China datapoints in her Macro Tracker to find them broadly encouraging, suggesting stabilisation in the 2H albeit off a low base, including the fact that luxury leather imports to China from Europe have turned positive for the first time since January 2024 which is the highest correlation statistic with underlying China growth that she watches (positive for LVMH (Buy, on CL).

Early stages of multi- year blockbuster Bimzelx ramp, optionality from pipeline beyond this

Rare opportunity within European Biopharma to own a significant blockbuster launch through Bimzelx. Rajan forecasts peak sales of the antibody drug Bimzelx of €7bn (12% ahead of consensus) across multiple rheumatology/dermatology indications (including psoriasis and Hidradenitis Suppurativa (HS)), underpinned by its best- in- class clinical data package, expert feedback and strong initial launch momentum. HS is a key opportunity within the indications, a chronic, inflammatory skin condition which only has 3 therapies currently approved including Bimzelx which is expected to be the leader as the market grows given expanded diagnosis rates and broader adoption of biologics.

Mid- stage portfolio of two drugs in atopic dermatitis (galvokimig and donzakimig) could also provide an additional leg of growth. Both assets have meaningful data updates in the next 12 months. At 1H25, galvokimig was in focus following initial encouraging data and management highlighted that potential differentiation of an asset with fast, durable and deep efficacy ahead of full data presentation at the EADV conference in September.

Uncertainty around US pricing for the sector more widely provides a good entry point. Recent volatility around tariffs and most favoured nation (MFN) pricing in the US have remained key investor concerns and been a significant overhang for UCB given its manufacturing footprint and pricing spread between the US and Europe for key drug Bimzelx. Although the stock has outperformed the SXDP by 10% YTD it has de- rated from 28x to 22x 12- month forward P/E (vs sector 14x to 12x) since its November 2024 peak despite upward revenue and earnings revisions which we see as an entry point to a long- term fundamental story.
Where are we different: Rajan is ahead of consensus on peak sales of Bimzelx (GSe \(\) 7bn\(, 12\%\$ ahead of consensus), leaving him \(4 - 6\%\) ahead on EBITDA over 2025- 27.

Catalysts: MLTX solenoidimbad data in September will be a catalyst, with the potential to remove an overhang assuming we do not see significant efficacy improvement and an inline safety profile which would create downside risk. Upcoming data in 2H for galvokimig and donzakimig (former at EADV 17- 20 Sept) could also bring more attention to the longer- term pipeline. Clarity on MFN pricing would remove wider sector overhang but timing of this would be uncertain.
Valuation: Rajan's €255 12m PT is based on a 50:50 blend between the DCF valuation (WACC of \(8\%\) , TGR of \(2\%\) ) and a P/E multiple- based approach (23x on 50:50 blend of 2026E and 2027E EPS).

Concerns on competitor data with the market focused on Phase 3 for MoonLake's (MLTX) solenoidimbax expected in September where initial Phase 2 data suggested potentially stronger headline efficiency but with nuances in trial design which may skew comparisons. Rajan expects MLTX to show statistically significant results but thinks that it would need to be a significant improvement relative to Bimzelx's Phase 3 with an inline safety profile to displace Bimzelx in HS given the c.3 year headstart UCB has to market which should allow it to build a strong formulary positioning as well as physician familiarity (especially as it is approved across multiple indications) which limits downside risk from the MLTX trial.
MFN pricing uncertainty continuing which would weigh on the broader sector, but given the de- rating UCB has already seen, this is well flagged already in his view.

Visibility on US energy policy to drive onshore order pick- up and offshore recovery creates room for cash returns

- US energy policy uncertainty is clearing, painting a positive order intake picture for H2. The recently announced Big Beautiful Bill and US IRA guidance for wind and solar tax credits removes a key uncertainty and paves the way for a strong uptick in US orders in the coming quarters (land-based wind pipeline of 28GW, per American Clean Power, can now start to convert). This alongside a stronger European order intake paints a picture of higher volumes and hence improved revenue growth, in Ajay's view. With higher volumes, he expects the margin recovery story for Vestas to continue as the company benefits from operational leverage.

- Offshore drag on margins to peak over 2H25. FY 2025 has been impacted by weaker performance in the offshore business. This has largely been through a combination of higher ramp-up costs and lower fixed cost absorption. Ajay sees ramp-up costs peaking over H2 which should de-risk the recovery of this business into next year. Furthermore, Vestas' secured backlog alongside orders that are expected to come should support higher revenue beyond FY 2025. Ajay expects group margins to move from c5% in 2025E to c7% in 2026E and c8% in 2027E as offshore revenues ramp up.

- Debate around cash returns should strengthen over H2. With a significant level of activity expected in H2, Ajay sees cash generation picking up sizeably increasing the scope for additional cash returns. He expects Vestas to increase buyback to £400m by the full year and sees this becoming an increasingly important feature of the Vestas investment case over the coming years. Ajay is 8% ahead of consensus on 2025 net cash.

Where are we different: For much of H1 the debate on Vestas has been around a slow recovery hampered by US energy policy uncertainty, risks surrounding the ramp- up of Vestas's offshore business and lower service margins. Ajay's view is that we are at a turning point given higher visibility on US energy policy combined with stronger

European orders supports his view of stronger top- line growth, which along with execution on the ramp- up of offshore over H2 further reduces the risk and supports profit margins. The end result is stronger cash flow than what is appreciated by consensus which should result in higher returns of cash to shareholders, in Ajay's view. While consensus EBIT remains high for FY25 and could be revised lower for one- off tariff impacts, these low multiple drivers should not distract from the two dominant factors for H2 of orders and cash generation, in Ajay's view.
Catalysts: Ajay expects Q3 on 5 Nov to show progress on order intake and signs that the offshore ramp has peaked and the cash flow inflection is starting to come through.

Valuation: Vestas trades on 11x EV/EBIT 2027E, a discount vs. the 15- year average (adjusted for outliers) of 13x (15x unadjusted) with upside risk to revenue growth and margins (based on \(8\%\) EBIT margin vs. group target for \(10\%\) ). Ajay's 12m PT of Dkr196 is based on a combination of a DCF (85% weighting, Dkr185/share; 7.2% post tax WACC; equates to 7x 2030E EV/EBIT) and an M&A valuation (15% weighting, Dkr259/share, 22x on 2030E EBIT ex- IRA growth basis based on historical transactions in Industrials in W Europe).

Crane- specific structural growth opportunity from US reshoring.

- Structural growth opportunity for Port Solutions given Chinese tariffs and incentives for US reshoring. Daniela sees significant upside risk to consensus for Port Solutions (35% of 2024 revenues) if proposals for a 100% tariff on Chinese-made ship-to-shore cranes in the US go ahead, and notes the prior US administration had already suggested legislation to replace all of the Chinese installed base in the US (final tariff decision anticipated in 2H25. Currently 80% of these cranes are supplied from China and Daniela sees Konecranes as well positioned given its 40% market share globally, and previously announced plan to develop a local supply network in the US. She sees two scenarios for Chinese cranes to be replaced by US made cranes: 1) a progressive ramp-up which assumes replacement over 15 years, driving a c.3% addition to annual group revenue growth (her base case), and 2) a steeper ramp-up over 10 years which would add c.6% to growth.

- Recovery in Industrial Equipment over the medium term driven by German infrastructure capex and US reshoring. While Daniela expects near-term weakness in Industrial Equipment (29% revenues) as global manufacturing capacity utilisation and US Industrial Real Estate Net Absorption (a key leading indicator) have been weak, she sees strong general industrial capex growth in the medium term supported by bonus depreciation in the US/Germany, as well as the exposure to German infrastructure spend with Konecranes deriving c.20% of revenues from Germany, one of the highest percentages across her coverage.

- Strong cash generation supports increased returns. Konecranes has a c.8% FCF yield in 2025E (top quartile vs. sector) and a net cash position. Daniela forecasts a buyback in 2026 which she expects to be announced with FY25 results (forecasts a c.4% buyback yield). With dividends, the FY26E total return yield would be 7%.

- Valuation is in line with 10-year history despite improvements. Both ROIC (from 9% in 2020 to 19% in 2025E) and cash conversion have improved but Konecranes trades on a 10.7x 12m forward EV/EBIT vs. 10.6x historical average. The PEG is also 1.1x, inexpensive vs. the sector PEG of 2.0x.
Where are we different: Daniela is 2- 6% above consensus on adj. EBIT 2025- 27E supported by a more positive view on Port Solutions and Industrial Equipment in outer
years but is \(4 - 16\%\) ahead on EPS helped by the buyback.

On October 1st 2023, we introduced this new investment list (European Conviction List - Directors' Cut), highlighting a selection of fundamental Buy- rated European stocks across the Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research department. This "Conviction List - Directors' Cut" is designed to provide investors with a curated and active list of 15- 25 of what we believe to be our most differentiated fundamental Buy ideas across our Europe stock coverage. We refresh and publish this list monthly in an easily digestible format that emphasises 1) the analyst's investment thesis, 2) where we are different, 3) key catalysts and 4) our analyst views on the big debates around each stock.

A subcommittee designated by the Europe Investment Review Committee will select stocks for the "Conviction List - Directors' Cut" from the Buy recommendations of European stocks. The subcommittee will collaborate with each sector analyst to identify top ideas that offer a combination of conviction, a differentiated view and high
risk- adjusted returns. The subcommittee will then choose what they view as the top 15- 25 ideas across the department for the list.

At the heart of the selection process is looking for ideas where our analysts see a different 'E' than is currently being contemplated by the market and the belief that earnings drive stocks over time. We are also focused on the catalyst path that will drive that 'E' higher over time.

We do not express thematic or factor views with this list. Rather, this list will focus on bottom- up fundamental ideas from our analysts. While our analysts routinely think about how macro impacts on the fundamentals of their stocks, we do not aim to express factor, rates, inflation or other macro views as we select names for this list.
Additionally, this list should not be seen as a portfolio, as we will not attempt to weight the included stocks or ensure diversification across our stock coverage.

Finally, inclusion on this list is not a stock rating and addition to, or removal from, this list does not necessarily represent a change in the analyst's investment rating for such stock. There are many reasons a stock could get removed from the list. They can include (but are not limited to), analysts no longer having conviction in their idea (e.g. a downgrade), price realisation, the passage of catalysts or the subcommittee believing there are better opportunities elsewhere. In short, names will be removed if this committee determines a name is no longer a top investment idea across our coverage.
